#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:4
msgid "argparse - parse options passed to a fish script or function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:7
msgid "Synopsis"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:9
msgid "argparse [OPTIONS] OPTION_SPEC ... -- [ARG ...]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:15
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:17
msgid ""
"This command makes it easy for fish scripts and functions to handle "
"arguments. You pass arguments that define the known options, followed by a "
"literal **--**, then the arguments to be parsed (which might also include a "
"literal **--**). ``argparse`` then sets variables to indicate the passed "
"options with their values, and sets ``$argv`` to the remaining arguments. "
"See the :ref:`usage <cmd-argparse-usage>` section below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:19
msgid ""
"Each option specification (``OPTION_SPEC``) is written in the :ref:`domain "
"specific language <cmd-argparse-option-specification>` described below. All "
"OPTION_SPECs must appear after any argparse flags and before the ``--`` that "
"separates them from the arguments to be parsed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:21
msgid ""
"Each option that is seen in the ARG list will result in variables named "
"``_flag_X``, where **X** is the short flag letter and the long flag name (if "
"they are defined). For example a **--help** option could cause argparse to "
"define one variable called ``_flag_h`` and another called ``_flag_help``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:23
msgid ""
"The variables will be set with local scope (i.e., as if the script had done "
"``set -l _flag_X``). If the flag is a boolean (that is, it just is passed or "
"not, it doesn't have a value) the values are the short and long flags seen. "
"If the option is not a boolean the values will be zero or more values "
"corresponding to the values collected when the ARG list is processed. If the "
"flag was not seen the flag variable will not be set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:26
msgid "Options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:28
msgid ""
"The following ``argparse`` options are available. They must appear before "
"all *OPTION_SPEC*\\ s:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:30
msgid "**-n** or **--name**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:31
msgid ""
"The command name for use in error messages. By default the current function "
"name will be used, or ``argparse`` if run outside of a function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:33
msgid "**-x** or **--exclusive** *OPTIONS*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:34
msgid ""
"A comma separated list of options that are mutually exclusive. You can use "
"this more than once to define multiple sets of mutually exclusive options. "
"You give either the short or long version of each option, and you still need "
"to otherwise define the options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:37
msgid "**-N** or **--min-args** *NUMBER*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:38
msgid ""
"The minimum number of acceptable non-option arguments. The default is zero."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:40
msgid "**-X** or **--max-args** *NUMBER*"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:41
msgid ""
"The maximum number of acceptable non-option arguments. The default is "
"infinity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:43
msgid "**-i** or **--ignore-unknown**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:44
msgid ""
"Ignores unknown options, keeping them and their arguments in $argv instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:46
msgid "**-s** or **--stop-nonopt**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:47
msgid ""
"Causes scanning the arguments to stop as soon as the first non-option "
"argument is seen. Among other things, this is useful to implement "
"subcommands that have their own options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:49
msgid "**-h** or **--help**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:50
msgid "Displays help about using this command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:55
msgid "Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:57
msgid ""
"To use this command, pass the option specifications (**OPTION_SPEC**), a "
"mandatory **--**, and then the arguments to be parsed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:59
msgid "A simple example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:61
msgid ""
"argparse --name=my_function 'h/help' 'n/name=' -- $argv\n"
"or return"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:64
msgid ""
"If ``$argv`` is empty then there is nothing to parse and ``argparse`` "
"returns zero to indicate success. If ``$argv`` is not empty then it is "
"checked for flags ``-h``, ``--help``, ``-n`` and ``--name``. If they are "
"found they are removed from the arguments and local variables called "
"``_flag_OPTION`` are set so the script can determine which options were "
"seen. If ``$argv`` doesn't have any errors, like a missing mandatory value "
"for an option, then ``argparse`` exits with a status of zero. Otherwise it "
"writes appropriate error messages to stderr and exits with a status of one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:66
msgid ""
"The ``or return`` means that the function returns ``argparse``'s status if "
"it failed, so if it goes on ``argparse`` succeeded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:68
msgid ""
"The ``--`` argument is required. You do not have to include any option "
"specifications or arguments after the ``--`` but you must include the ``--"
"``. For example, this is acceptable::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:70
msgid ""
"set -l argv foo\n"
"argparse 'h/help' 'n/name' -- $argv\n"
"argparse --min-args=1 -- $argv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:74
msgid "But this is not::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:76
msgid ""
"set -l argv\n"
"argparse 'h/help' 'n/name' $argv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:79
msgid ""
"The first ``--`` seen is what allows the ``argparse`` command to reliably "
"separate the option specifications and options to ``argparse`` itself (like "
"``--ignore-unknown``) from the command arguments, so it is required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:84
msgid "Option Specifications"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:86
msgid "Each option specification consists of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:88
msgid ""
"An optional alphanumeric short flag character, followed by a ``/`` if the "
"short flag can be used by someone invoking your command or, for backwards "
"compatibility, a ``-`` if it should not be exposed as a valid short flag (in "
"which case it will also not be exposed as a flag variable)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:90
msgid ""
"An optional long flag name, which if not present the short flag can be used, "
"and if that is also not present, an error is reported"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:92
msgid ""
"Nothing if the flag is a boolean that takes no argument or is an integer "
"flag, or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:94
msgid ""
"**=** if it requires a value and only the last instance of the flag is "
"saved, or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:96
msgid ""
"**=?** if it takes an optional value and only the last instance of the flag "
"is saved, or"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:98
msgid "**=+** if it requires a value and each instance of the flag is saved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:100
msgid ""
"Optionally a ``!`` followed by fish script to validate the value. Typically "
"this will be a function to run. If the exit status is zero the value for the "
"flag is valid. If non-zero the value is invalid. Any error messages should "
"be written to stdout (not stderr). See the section on :ref:`Flag Value "
"Validation <flag-value-validation>` for more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:102
msgid ""
"See the :doc:`fish_opt <fish_opt>` command for a friendlier but more verbose "
"way to create option specifications."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:104
msgid ""
"If a flag is not seen when parsing the arguments then the corresponding "
"_flag_X var(s) will not be set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:107
msgid "Integer flag"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:109
msgid ""
"Sometimes commands take numbers directly as options, like ``foo -55``. To "
"allow this one option spec can have the ``#`` modifier so that any integer "
"will be understood as this flag, and the last number will be given as its "
"value (as if ``=`` was used)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:111
msgid ""
"The ``#`` must follow the short flag letter (if any), and other modifiers "
"like ``=`` are not allowed, except for ``-`` (for backwards compatibility)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:113
msgid "m#maximum"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:115
msgid ""
"This does not read numbers given as ``+NNN``, only those that look like "
"flags - ``-NNN``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:118
msgid "Note: Optional arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:120
msgid ""
"An option defined with ``=?`` can take optional arguments. Optional "
"arguments have to be *directly attached* to the option they belong to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:122
msgid ""
"That means the argument will only be used for the option if you use it like::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:124
msgid ""
"cmd --flag=value\n"
"# or\n"
"cmd  -fvalue"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:128
msgid "but not if used like::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:130
msgid ""
"cmd --flag value\n"
"# \"value\" here will be used as a positional argument\n"
"# and \"--flag\" won't have an argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:134
msgid ""
"If this weren't the case, using an option without an optional argument would "
"be difficult if you also wanted to use positional arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:136
msgid "For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:138
msgid ""
"grep --color auto\n"
"# Here \"auto\" will be used as the search string,\n"
"# \"color\" will not have an argument and will fall back to the default,\n"
"# which also *happens to be* auto.\n"
"grep --color always\n"
"# Here grep will still only use color \"auto\"matically\n"
"# and search for the string \"always\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:146
msgid ""
"This isn't specific to argparse but common to all things using ``getopt(3)`` "
"(if they have optional arguments at all). That ``grep`` example is how GNU "
"grep actually behaves."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:151
msgid "Flag Value Validation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:153
msgid ""
"Sometimes you need to validate the option values. For example, that it is a "
"valid integer within a specific range, or an ip address, or something "
"entirely different. You can always do this after ``argparse`` returns but "
"you can also request that ``argparse`` perform the validation by executing "
"arbitrary fish script. To do so simply append an ``!`` (exclamation-mark) "
"then the fish script to be run. When that code is executed three vars will "
"be defined:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:155
msgid ""
"``_argparse_cmd`` will be set to the value of the value of the ``argparse --"
"name`` value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:157
msgid ""
"``_flag_name`` will be set to the short or long flag that being processed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:159
msgid ""
"``_flag_value`` will be set to the value associated with the flag being "
"processed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:161
msgid "These variables are passed to the function as local exported variables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:163
msgid ""
"The script should write any error messages to stdout, not stderr. It should "
"return a status of zero if the flag value is valid otherwise a non-zero "
"status to indicate it is invalid."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:165
msgid ""
"Fish ships with a ``_validate_int`` function that accepts a ``--min`` and "
"``--max`` flag. Let's say your command accepts a ``-m`` or ``--max`` flag "
"and the minimum allowable value is zero and the maximum is 5. You would "
"define the option like this: ``m/max=!_validate_int --min 0 --max 5``. The "
"default if you just call ``_validate_int`` without those flags is to simply "
"check that the value is a valid integer with no limits on the min or max "
"value allowed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:167
msgid "Here are some examples of flag validations::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:169
msgid ""
"# validate that a path is a directory\n"
"argparse 'p/path=!test -d \"$_flag_value\"' -- --path $__fish_config_dir\n"
"# validate that a function does not exist\n"
"argparse 'f/func=!not functions -q \"$_flag_value\"' -- -f alias\n"
"# validate that a string matches a regex\n"
"argparse 'c/color=!string match -rq \\'^#?[0-9a-fA-F]{6}$\\' "
"\"$_flag_value\"' -- -c 'c0ffee'\n"
"# validate with a validator function\n"
"argparse 'n/num=!_validate_int --min 0 --max 99' -- --num 42"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:179
msgid "Example OPTION_SPECs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:181
msgid "Some *OPTION_SPEC* examples:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:183
msgid ""
"``h/help`` means that both ``-h`` and ``--help`` are valid. The flag is a "
"boolean and can be used more than once. If either flag is used then "
"``_flag_h`` and ``_flag_help`` will be set to however either flag was seen, "
"as many times as it was seen. So it could be set to ``-h``, ``-h`` and ``--"
"help``, and ``count $_flag_h`` would yield \"3\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:185
msgid ""
"``help`` means that only ``--help`` is valid. The flag is a boolean and can "
"be used more than once. If it is used then ``_flag_help`` will be set as "
"above. Also ``h-help`` (with an arbitrary short letter) for backwards "
"compatibility."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:187
msgid ""
"``longonly=`` is a flag ``--longonly`` that requires an option, there is no "
"short flag or even short flag variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:189
msgid ""
"``n/name=`` means that both ``-n`` and ``--name`` are valid. It requires a "
"value and can be used at most once. If the flag is seen then ``_flag_n`` and "
"``_flag_name`` will be set with the single mandatory value associated with "
"the flag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:191
msgid ""
"``n/name=?`` means that both ``-n`` and ``--name`` are valid. It accepts an "
"optional value and can be used at most once. If the flag is seen then "
"``_flag_n`` and ``_flag_name`` will be set with the value associated with "
"the flag if one was provided else it will be set with no values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:193
msgid ""
"``name=+`` means that only ``--name`` is valid. It requires a value and can "
"be used more than once. If the flag is seen then ``_flag_name`` will be set "
"with the values associated with each occurrence."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:195
msgid ""
"``x`` means that only ``-x`` is valid. It is a boolean that can be used more "
"than once. If it is seen then ``_flag_x`` will be set as above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:197
msgid ""
"``x=``, ``x=?``, and ``x=+`` are similar to the n/name examples above but "
"there is no long flag alternative to the short flag ``-x``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:199
msgid ""
"``#max`` (or ``#-max``) means that flags matching the regex \"^--?\\\\d+$\" "
"are valid. When seen they are assigned to the variable ``_flag_max``. This "
"allows any valid positive or negative integer to be specified by prefixing "
"it with a single \"-\". Many commands support this idiom. For example ``head "
"-3 /a/file`` to emit only the first three lines of /a/file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:201
msgid ""
"``n#max`` means that flags matching the regex \"^--?\\\\d+$\" are valid. "
"When seen they are assigned to the variables ``_flag_n`` and ``_flag_max``. "
"This allows any valid positive or negative integer to be specified by "
"prefixing it with a single \"-\". Many commands support this idiom. For "
"example ``head -3 /a/file`` to emit only the first three lines of /a/file. "
"You can also specify the value using either flag: ``-n NNN`` or ``--max "
"NNN`` in this example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:203
msgid ""
"``#longonly`` causes the last integer option to be stored in "
"``_flag_longonly``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:205
msgid ""
"After parsing the arguments the ``argv`` variable is set with local scope to "
"any values not already consumed during flag processing. If there are no "
"unbound values the variable is set but ``count $argv`` will be zero."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:207
msgid ""
"If an error occurs during argparse processing it will exit with a non-zero "
"status and print error messages to stderr."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:210
msgid "Examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:212
msgid "A simple use::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:214
msgid ""
"argparse h/help -- $argv\n"
"or return\n"
"\n"
"if set -q _flag_help\n"
"    # TODO: Print help here\n"
"    return 0\n"
"end"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:222
msgid ""
"This just wants one option - ``-h`` / ``--help``. Any other option is an "
"error. If it is given it prints help and exits."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:224
msgid "How :doc:`fish_add_path` parses its args::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:226
msgid ""
"argparse -x g,U -x P,U -x a,p g/global U/universal P/path p/prepend a/append "
"h/help m/move v/verbose n/dry-run -- $argv"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:228
msgid ""
"There are a variety of boolean flags, all with long and short versions. A "
"few of these cannot be used together, and that is what the ``-x`` flag is "
"used for. ``-x g,U`` means that ``--global`` and ``--universal`` or their "
"short equivalents conflict, and if they are used together you get an error. "
"In this case you only need to give the short or long flag, not the full "
"option specification."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:232
msgid ""
"After this it figures out which variable it should operate on according to "
"the ``--path`` flag::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:234
msgid ""
"set -l var fish_user_paths\n"
"set -q _flag_path\n"
"and set var PATH"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:241
msgid "Limitations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:243
msgid ""
"One limitation with **--ignore-unknown** is that, if an unknown option is "
"given in a group with known options, the entire group will be kept in $argv. "
"``argparse`` will not do any permutations here."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:245
msgid "For instance::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:247
msgid ""
"argparse --ignore-unknown h -- -ho\n"
"echo $_flag_h # is -h, because -h was given\n"
"echo $argv # is still -ho"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:251
msgid "This limitation may be lifted in future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../cmds/argparse.rst:253
msgid ""
"Additionally, it can only parse known options up to the first unknown option "
"in the group - the unknown option could take options, so it isn't clear what "
"any character after an unknown option means."
msgstr ""
